{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":907,"record_hash":"sha256:5afdc8864fff6cefe1aea1a21b6e12c877473a97ca6faf0f1b1be0c6a662b7bf","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:32.433Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Delete File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/session-association-strategy.md\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/session-association-strategy.md\n+# Session Association Strategy\n+\n+> [!NOTE]\n+> This is historical background, not the active implementation plan. The current\n+> direction is [Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md).\n+\n+This note captures the association lessons that still matter after the move to\n+turn-based capture.\n+\n+The old strategy explored explicit attach, commit-time confirmation, review\n+pickers, active session pins, change-id links, commit SHA links, and\n+evidence-based recomputation. That comparison was useful, but the active plan is\n+now simpler:\n+\n+```text\n+capture observations -> write derived lookup indexes -> score associations on read\n+```\n+\n+V1 should not require a human confirmation step. It also should not automatically\n+persist inferred relationships as durable truth. Capture records facts. Read\n+paths derive likely related sessions with confidence labels and reasons.\n+\n+## Current Direction\n+\n+- Keep the durable transcript object project-scoped:\n+\n+  ```text\n+  project\n+    gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n+  ```\n+\n+- Add capture turns under each session:\n+\n+  ```text\n+  one session -> many capture turns -> many transcript records\n+  ```\n+\n+- Store environment observations on each turn: worktree files, stacks, branches,\n+  review identifiers, change ids, commit ids, and path-only commit file lists.\n+- Write derived lookup indexes for branch, review, and change candidates.\n+- Do not write a path index in v1.\n+- Compute association results at read time from indexed candidates plus turn\n+  details.\n+- Show high-confidence related sessions automatically, with reasons.\n+- Phrase results as \"likely related session evidence\", not provenance proof.\n+\n+## Durable Links\n+\n+The existing explicit relationship shape may still exist:\n+\n+```text\n+<target>\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+If present, these explicit links should be treated as strong evidence. They are\n+not the default v1 association mechanism.\n+\n+Future product/API flows may add durable target-to-session relationships with\n+optional turn scope, but that should be a later decision. It should mean \"this\n+session is relevant to this target\", not \"this session generated this target.\"\n+\n+## Why Not Capture-Time Ownership\n+\n+Capture-time ownership is brittle:\n+\n+- the current branch may be unrelated to the agent's work\n+- a GitButler workspace can contain multiple applied branches\n+- a session can span several branches or reviews\n+- generated edits can be split, moved, squashed, discarded, or mixed with manual\n+  edits later\n+- plain Git operations can bypass GitButler metadata lifecycle hooks\n+\n+False positives are worse than missed links because they can mislead reviewers\n+about how code was produced.\n+\n+Capture should therefore write observations and indexes, not final inferred\n+ownership claims.\n+\n+## Useful Signals\n+\n+The active scoring model lives in\n+[Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md), but the important signal\n+ordering is:\n+\n+- direct explicit links, if present, are strongest\n+- previous-turn worktree files later appearing in observed commit file lists is\n+  strong evidence\n+- directly observed change ids, review ids, or pull request ids are strong\n+  candidate evidence\n+- branch-name observation is useful but weak by itself\n+- repeated observation strengthens a session-level result\n+- broad/truncated file lists, many visible branches, and failed environment\n+  snapshots weaken confidence\n+\n+## Lifecycle Risks\n+\n+Durable relationships, if added later, still have lifecycle risks:\n+\n+- amend can add new relevant turns to an existing change\n+- uncommit/recommit can orphan or blur links\n+- split or move operations can divide evidence across destinations\n+- squash can merge several evidence sources into one surviving change\n+- reorder/rebase changes commit ids\n+- branch rename/delete/recreate can make branch-level links stale\n+- undo/redo can replay stale metadata\n+- plain Git operations can bypass relationship maintenance\n+\n+That lifecycle footprint is the main reason v1 prefers derived read-time\n+association results over persisted inferred links.\n+\n+## Change IDs\n+\n+Change ids remain the best future code-level anchor, but they are not magic:\n+\n+- synthetic change ids derived from commit ids are not durable across rewrites\n+- squash may keep one surviving change id and drop others\n+- uncommit/recommit can break continuity unless GitButler preserves identity\n+- plain Git operations can bypass GitButler's ability to maintain links\n+\n+For v1, change ids are useful association evidence and index keys. They are not\n+the basis for automatic durable relationship propagation.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:32.433Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}